## Frequently Asked Questions

**Is the minimal manicure trend just a seasonal thing or a long-term shift?**

The data suggests a structural shift rather than a seasonal pattern. Fresha recorded 250% year-on-year growth in minimal manicure bookings for spring 2026 against spring 2025 — which was itself a period of significant growth for the category. Autumn forecasters are pointing toward richer, moodier iterations of the same clean, low-complexity aesthetic, not toward maximalism replacing it. Multiple brands including OPI, CND, and Essie have deepened their sheer and milky professional shade ranges for 2026, which reflects a multi-year commercial commitment.

**How should nail techs price a minimal manicure?**

A sheer gel manicure requires the same or more time than a coloured gel set and places higher demands on prep precision — a milky or sheer finish shows every imperfection in nail plate preparation. It should be priced at or above a standard gel manicure. Zenoti's 2025 benchmark data places gel manicures at $35–$60 on average in the US, with metro techs running $65–$85. Minimal manicures positioned as a technique-forward, high-finish service belong at the premium end of that range. Positioning logic: the client is paying for cuticle work quality and finish precision, not colour complexity.

**What products should nail techs stock for the minimal manicure trend?**

Rubber base gel and builder gel are identified by Spate as among the fastest-growing professional product categories in 2026, and they underpin the minimal manicure technically — delivering the strength, longevity, and skin-tone clarity that clients requesting sheer finishes expect. Sheer and milky gel polishes in the Essie Marshmallow, OPI Bubble Bath, and OPI Funny Bunny range (all reformulated for Spring 2026 GelColor) are the commercial anchors. Cuticle oil and nail strengtheners are the highest-converting retail items for clients in this category.

**Will clients requesting minimal manicures rebook at a lower rate than art clients?**

Evidence from professional nail business education points in the opposite direction. Clients requesting sheer, maintenance-focused finishes tend to be establishing a recurring routine rather than booking occasional statement looks. Rebooking behaviour is higher in the maintenance category. The service revenue per appointment may be lower than a complex art set, but the client lifetime value and calendar reliability are typically stronger.

**Is the minimal manicure only popular in the UK, or is this a global trend?**

Fresha's booking data covers a global salon network across 120-plus countries. The 250% year-on-year growth figure reflects global appointment volume, with the UK data point being specifically reported by TheIndustry.beauty. In the US, Spate's Popularity Index tracks Google, TikTok, and Instagram simultaneously — and has flagged sheer and nude nail categories as among the fastest-growing professional nail searches in 2026. US salon chains have also flagged shorter-nail and sheer-finish demand building for over a year, according to PBL Magazine's market analysis.

